Table 4: Combination of SWAD and other methods. The scores are averaged over every target domain case.

The performances of ERM, CORAL, and SAM are optimized by HP searches of DomainBed. In contrast, for the 
SWAD combination cases, CORAL and SAM use default HPs without additional HP search. We additionally 
compare SWAD to SWAw/ const. Note that ERM + SWAD is same as "SWAD" in Table 2.

Table 5: Ablation studies of the stochastic weights selection strategies on PACS and VLCS. In the configura-

tion, "ts", "te", "lr", and "interval" indicate start and end iterations of sampling, a learning rate schedule, and 
a stochastic weight sampling interval, respectively. "Opt" and "Overfit" indicate the start and end iterations 
identified by our overfit-aware sampling strategy, and "Val" means the start and end iterations whose averaging 
shows the best accuracy on the validation set. "Cyclic" and "Const" represent cyclic and constant learning rate 
schedules. All experiments are repeated three times.
